I made a few changes to accommodate the ingredients I had on hand - I doubled the recipe and used about 1 cup whole milk and the rest 2% milk, and I made my own "pumpkin pie spice". I also dried the challah bread cubes in the oven for about 5 minutes (at 300 degrees) before soaking them in the pumpkin mixture, and lightly buttered the casserole dish before pouring the pudding into it. I made this the night before Thanksgiving, and then reheated the whole casserole covered with foil in a warm oven (and made the caramel sauce while the pudding was warming) after dinner. I'll be honest - I wasn't too pleased with it. I thought it was too pumpkin-y and didn't really like the texture. HOWEVER - the leftovers we've eaten since Thanksgiving are fantastic! It really does get better and better each day that it sits in the fridge - we're two days past Thanksgiving and I can't stop eating it (lots of leftovers). The caramel sauce keeps well in an airtight container as well. Delicious - but if I were to make this again I'd make it a few days in advance and reheat the night of the dinner.

