Rating: 4
This recipe was delicious and a huge hit with my guests. I will definitely be making it again. I used Challah, adding an extra splash of milk. Also, I didn't have pumpkin pie spice but ended up just adding a bit of ginger and clove. And instead of the recommended caramel sauce, I served this with bourbon sauce... mmmmmm. Bourbon Sauce: Melt 1/2 stick unsalted butter in top of double boiler set over simmering water. Add 3 tablespoons bourbon, 1/4 cup sugar and 1 egg yolk. Whisk until mixture thickens slightly and candy thermometer registers 160°F, about 1 minute. Remove from heat.

Rating: 4
I often come to Epicurious to figure out what to cook, based on what I have on hand. In this case, I had 4 egg whites I needed to use up, along with some commercial egg nog (gingerbread flavored). Since I knew I was experimenting, I had already lowered my expectations, but it actually worked! I did have to reduce the sugar in the custard mixture to accommodate for the extra sweetness in the egg nog. And, as others, I played around with the seasoning a bit. Didn't add raisins (again, I was experimenting) and was fine without them. Now for the truly decadent part - after reading another reviewer's suggestion to shape these into columns for individual ramekins, I thought, why not shape into slices for a truly decadent FRENCH TOAST? No need to dip "bread" into eggs, since they're already in there. Just saute in butter over medium heat, add maple syrup and voila! Best French toast I've ever had! ******* Will make my version again and also try recipe per its original ingredients list, but this is a keeper because it's easy to tweak.

